ng's is a richly informed, radical voice that boldly confronts issues of crucial importance to the future of many academic disciplines. Her book will amply reward readers looking to achieve a more fruitful understanding of the relations between feminism, science, and social life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminist theory. 0aKnowledge, Theory of. 0aSciencexSocial aspects. 0aScience. 0aWomen in science. 0aWomenxEmployment. 0aWorking class women. 4aHistory Of Science. 4aHistory. 4aWomens Studies.  aEpistemology philosophy.  aEpistemology.  aFeminisms.  aFeminist Epistemology.  aFeminist activism.  aFeminist analysis.  aFeminist discourse.  aFeminist education.  aFeminist literature.  aGender & Society.  aSocial Research.  aThe Science Question in Feminism.  aWomen's Studies.  aepistemology.  afeminism and methodology.  afeminism and science.  afeminism and society.  afeminism.  afeminist approach to science.  afeminist critique.  afeminist knowledge theory.  afeminist perspective.  afeminist science studies scholar.  afeminist sociology.  afeminist studies.  afeminist theory.  agender studies.  ahistory of philosophy.  aintro to feminism.  aintroduction to feminism.  aknowledge.  amale feminist.  amodernity studies.  aphilosophical feminist theories.  aphilosophy of science.  aphilosophy.  ascience theory.  ascientific knowledge.  asociology.  atheory.  aunderstanding feminism.  awomen in science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171295140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501712951423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501712951/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Pres